I waited 19 years to have the opportunity to kiss, hug, and hold my daughter. Sometimes these situations don’t play out the best and this moment could of never happened. I’m leaving New York feeling complete and at peace. I didn’t know if she was really going to come see me. The last few times had its challenges so it was difficult for us to come together and timing played a big factor in it as well. We needed to build and create a relationship that we didn’t have…so things could be right. Patience was key. I definitely apologize to those I didn’t get to see but I’m sure you all understand. My focus was enjoying every moment to see my child smile in person. Next time it’ll be all of us together as a family and I can’t wait! Definitely learned a lot this trip! It was great to sit with her adoptive family that raised her and show my love and respect for showing up in the ways I couldn’t back then. Life has been a journey and I’m just grateful throughout this journey things are finally coming together and leading me to peace. Much love family! #thvPORTAHs

Empathic listening is a structured listening and questioning technique that allows you to develop and enhance relationships with a stronger understanding of what is being conveyed, both intellectually and emotionally.

Assertiveness means expressing your point of view in a way that is clear and direct, while still respecting others.

When we want to change the results! We have to alter what we are doing! Remember body language and tone play a VERY big part when communicating. These are things to start changing to have a better result in your relationship. Much love family. #thvPORTAHs

The beautiful part on your journey in Non-Monogamy?! Is the journey of self-discovery. Learning healthier ways to communicate, learn your emotional triggers, working on conflict resolution as one, and the overall mental strength and self-understanding you achieve! I’m not saying you can’t acquire these things in monogamy. But having multiple partners puts you in a position to self-reflect with no room of avoidance. If you’re monogamous or non-monogamous! Self work is a must for a healthy relationship and overall peaceful life. Much love family!

Non-monogamous individuals are very aware of what they are involved in. It’s a consensual agreement from all parties which takes tremendous amount of assertive emotional communication amongst each other. No! The journey is not easy at times. But the path is clear cause of the level of healthy communication it takes. We don’t have the delusion that all revolves around us. We understand we must provide room for growth as we each evolve and create spaces to be vulnerable and transparent with each other. There are levels to the self work and team work it takes to have a successful healthy non-monogamous relationship. So there is no room for ownership or control when you take time to understand each other with patience and grace. Much love family. #thvPORTAHs

One of the wonderful financial perks of a Poly-relationship? Is knowing whatever financial challenges may come or alterations that may be needed from a attending school for a new career path, being a stay home parent, or a moment of being in-between jobs. This book isn't centered around polyamory or any specific poly-related topics. There are already plenty of resources available on those subjects. Instead, its focus is on cultivating self-growth, self-awareness, and emotional intelligence, which are essential tools for encourage positive character development for any form of relationship. Kitchen Table Polyamory is an approach to non-monogamous relationships where all partners involved are encouraged to have open and direct communication with each other. Everyone sitting around a kitchen table, sharing their experiences and feelings. This style gives a sense of community and emotional connection among all members of the polycule, even if they aren’t romantically involved with each other. Issues are typically addressed collectively, emphasizing the importance of transparency and interconnection among all partners.

Parallel Polyamory is a different approach, where each romantic relationship exists relatively independently of the others. Partners in parallel polyamory may not have as much direct interaction or communication with each other, and they often maintain distinct boundaries and separate social circles for their relationships. Each relationship handles issues privately, without significant involvement of other partners. This approach respects the autonomy of each relationship while still adhering to the principles of consensual non-monogamy. Let’s keep learning and growing together! Much love family. #thvPORTAHs

Remember that non-monogamous relationships require open communication, consent, and often well-defined boundaries to ensure the well-being and happiness of everyone involved. Each type of non-monogamy has its unique dynamics and practices. Let’s keep learning together! Choice over default. Much love family. #thvPORTAHs

Here are some additional questions that can help facilitate discussions with your spouse while dating in a non-monogamous relationship:

1. How do you envision our non-monogamous relationship working for both of us?
2. What are your boundaries and comfort levels when it comes to dating others?
3. How often should we check in with each other about our other relationships?
4. Are there specific sexual health practices or guidelines we should establish?
5. What types of relationships are you interested in pursuing (casual, serious, etc.)?
6. How would you like us to handle scheduling and time management with multiple partners?
7. Are there any specific emotional needs or concerns you have about non-monogamy?
8. How do you want to handle disclosure of new relationships or experiences?
9. What role do you see our primary relationship playing in our non-monogamous journey?
10. How can we ensure that our non-monogamous relationships enhance our connection rather than threaten it?

These questions can serve as a starting point for productive discussions, but it’s important to tailor them to your specific situation and always be receptive to your partner’s feelings and needs. Communication and mutual understanding are key to making non-monogamy work. Let’s keep learning and growing together! Much love family!🫡👑🖤🔥 #thvPORTAHs

There is a significant difference in a few things about poly!

1. Polygyny and Polyamory are not the same! Polygyny, found under polygamy, is marriage-based. This means an agreement and contract are in place, mirroring a marriage license as in monogamy. Polyamory, meaning “many loves,” doesn’t require, at times nor desire, those measures. It is solely based on loving, lifetime connections.

2. Cheating is not polygamy, polygyny, polyamorous, poly-anything! Cheating is betrayal, deceit, lies, and misleading. An agreement made between all parties to have other partners is consensual. There is no betrayal, no deceit, or lies. There’s a big difference!!

3. The relationship dynamic will not determine the child’s mindset. It’s the tools we apply and morals in our children that will! It’s about creating healthy homes and families for our children to have the best relationships that will be healthy for them!

Levels.

Polyamory and Polygamy are both forms of consensual non-monogamous relationships, but they have distinct differences. Polyamory involves individuals engaging in multiple romantic or sexual relationships with the consent of all parties involved. It emphasizes emotional connections and often lacks a specific structure.

On the other hand, polygamy specifically refers to a marriage arrangement where one person is married to multiple spouses simultaneously. Polygamy is often associated with cultural or religious contexts and may have a more defined structure, such as polygyny (one man with multiple wives) or polyandry (one woman with multiple husbands). While polyamory focuses on relationships, polygamy centers around marriage arrangements. Much love family! Let’s keep growing and learning together!! #thvPORTAHs 🫡👑💯💎🤲🏽
